result.execSummary:
The defendant David J West was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Pay costs at the rate of $40.00 per month, starting November 1, 2015 and on the same day thereafter, until paid in full.    Failure to pay any part of the court costs in full by the due date will result in 1 day jail for each $25 left unpaid.
May apply for expungement at age 21 if he has no new criminal convictions for offenses that occurred after 9/14/15.

ADA Melissa Inlow appears for the State.  Defendant appeared in person, in custody, with Attorney Sebion.  Preliminary hearing canceled.  State moved to amend Count 1 to Misd. BJ.   Motion amend granted.  Defendant plead guilty to the amended charge.  Court advised the defendant of the elements of the amended charge.  He understood.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights with the defendant.  Defendant understood.  Defense stipulated to a factual basis for the amended charge.  Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty of Misd. Bail Jumping. Joint recommendation for 30 days jail.  Credit for 16 days.  Defendant elected to exercise his right to allocution.  Court ordered:   30 days jail.  Credit for 16 days.  CC.  Pay @ $40.00/mo.  11/1/15.  May apply for expungement at age 21 if he has no new criminal convictions for offenses that occurred after 9/14/15.
Attorney Sebion requests signature bond.  Conditions impossible to comply at school.  State responded.  Court denied request.
